[1] Cholera - Afghanistan (Ghazni)
Date: Tue 31 Aug 2010
Source: Central Asia Online [edited]
<http://centralasiaonline.com/cocoon/caii/xhtml/en_GB/newsbriefs/caii/newsbriefs/2010/08/31/newsbrief-13>


Afghanistan's Ministry of Public Health and the World Health
Organization (WHO) say a cholera outbreak in the northern province of
Ghazni has been brought under control, according to a WHO press release.

The outbreak, which sickened at least 130 people in the Nowa
district, began 9 Aug 2010, when a health NGO (non-governmental
organization) confirmed the 60 initial cases through laboratory
testing. The Ministry of Public Health and the WHO immediately
deployed staff with emergency medical supplies to treat the outbreak.
Since then, the outbreak has slowed to just 3 new cases daily, the
WHO reported in its release.

Diarrheal diseases are common in Afghanistan, where just 23 percent
of residents have access to safe drinking water. To limit the expanse
of outbreaks, Afghanistan has created the Disease Early Warning
System, which is now operational in 284 districts in all 34
provinces, with more than 300 surveillance officers tracking disease outbreaks

